The essay that follows is based upon a presentation given at the April 2004 Global Forum for Media Development on “New Media, Authoritarian Regimes and the Right to Communicate” in Saint Petersburg, Russia. It was published in “Journalism inAuthoritarian Contexts,” Knowledge, Communication and Social Policies Series, Node 5 (ESA working papers Number 5, January 2005).
Andrea L. Cinnamon University of Florida Day in and day out, women journalists around the world find themselves facing new challenges as part of their professional lives. Unfortunately, in most cases, it is their sex that continues to pose the greatest obstacle to their success. Despite efforts to address the inequalities under which they work, particular aspects of their experiences are still dominant. Some may be expected, while some seem out of place in an industry that is in a state of dramatic and unprecedented transformation.
